STAT656: Introductory Flight Example

Getting oriented with R, R Markdown, and tidying

Reading in the data

We want to load in the data (after inspecting it in some manner e.g. the unix command ‘head -3 934548400_T_ONTIME_REPORTING.csv’). We can alternatively inspect it through R itself:

readLines('934548400_T_ONTIME_REPORTING.csv', n = 3)
## [1] "\"DAY_OF_MONTH\",\"ORIGIN_AIRPORT_ID\",\"ORIGIN_AIRPORT_SEQ_ID\",\"ORIGIN_CITY_MARKET_ID\",\"ORIGIN\",\"DEP_DELAY\",\"DEP_DELAY_NEW\",\"DEP_DEL15\","
## [2] "1,11618,1161802,31703,\"EWR\",-5.00,0.00,0.00,"                                                                                                      
## [3] "1,12889,1288903,32211,\"LAS\",-8.00,0.00,0.00,"

We find that there is a mixture of numeric and string data. ALso, there is a trailing empty column due to the comma ending each line. The read.csv function automatically interprets strings as factors. We are going to sub-select from the levels of this qualitative explanatory variable, so we don’t want it to create a factor on import (after reading/experimenting with factors, why would this matter?)

flightData = read.csv('934548400_T_ONTIME_REPORTING.csv',header=TRUE,stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

Now, we would want to see if what we got is what we expect. For instance, the dimensions are 570118, 9.

Some data structure comments

In computer science, a data structure is a storage format for information. We have seen one so far:

Strings/Characters

stringExample = 'any quoted is a string'
print(stringExample)
## [1] "any quoted is a string"
paste(stringExample,"double quotes also work",sep='; ')
## [1] "any quoted is a string; double quotes also work"
is.character(stringExample)
## [1] TRUE
typeof(stringExample)
## [1] "character"

Floats and integers

floatExample = 1
print(floatExample)
## [1] 1
is.double(floatExample)
## [1] TRUE
typeof(floatExample)
## [1] "double"
object.size(floatExample)
## 56 bytes

data.frame

By default, the output of read.csv is a data.frame. This can be checked in a several ways, namely

is.data.frame(flightData)
## [1] TRUE

We are going to be using a very nice implementation of the “Split-Apply-Combine” idea known as the tidyverse. The first step is to convert the object from a data.frame to a tibble.

Installing/loading packages

R works by having some base functions that are always loaded (e.g. typeof). To keep things uncluttered, all the extra functionality are kept in packages that must be installed and the loaded into memory. Let’s do just that with the tidyverse package:

if(!require(tidyverse)){install.packages('tidyverse');require(tidyverse)}

Back to the question

In there any difference in delay length in January 2018 between IAH or DFW?

Continuing to convert this to a statistical question, we can look into testing if the population mean delay time at IAH equals the population mean delay time at DFW.

Let’s use split/apply/combine to get the relevant information. A good metaphor for thinking about this is in terms of `grammar’; there are nouns (the objects) and verbs (the functions). We will keep exploring this idea, but here is brief glimpse

flightDataTB_originDelay       = select(flightDataTB,ORIGIN,DEP_DELAY_NEW,DEP_DELAY)
flightDataTB_originDelayIAHDFW = filter(flightDataTB_originDelay, ORIGIN == 'IAH' | ORIGIN == 'DFW')
dim(flightDataTB_originDelayIAHDFW)
## [1] 36407     3

Before we get too far here, let’s make an adjustment to this code. Notice how we are getting complicated object names and writing very similar things over and over? It is very easy for typos and bugs to appear in your code this way. Pipes to the rescue!

flightDataTB  %>% 
  select(ORIGIN,DEP_DELAY_NEW, DEP_DELAY) %>%
  filter(ORIGIN == 'IAH' | ORIGIN == 'DFW') %>%
  dim(.)
## [1] 36407     3

Much cleaner, easier to read, and debug. Now, we are free to investigate the question statistically.

(Ybar = flightDataTB  %>% 
  select(ORIGIN,DAY_OF_MONTH, DEP_DELAY_NEW, DEP_DELAY) %>%
  filter(ORIGIN == 'IAH' | ORIGIN == 'DFW') %>%
  group_by(ORIGIN) %>%
  summarise(Ybar = mean(DEP_DELAY_NEW, na.rm = TRUE)))
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   ORIGIN  Ybar
##   <chr>  <dbl>
## 1 DFW     9.88
## 2 IAH    10.9

So, we get Ybar_IAH = 10.8856075 and Ybar_DFW = 9.8821943. It’s not surprising, of course, to find that the sample means are not equal. Let’s form a confidence interval via a pooled two-sample t-test:

flightDataTB_ttest = flightDataTB  %>% 
  select(ORIGIN, DAY_OF_MONTH, DEP_DELAY_NEW, DEP_DELAY) %>%
  filter(ORIGIN == 'IAH' | ORIGIN == 'DFW')

confint(lm(DEP_DELAY_NEW ~ ORIGIN, data = flightDataTB_ttest))
##                2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 9.382367 10.382021
## ORIGINIAH   0.191981  1.814845

Of course, no statistical method should be applied without looking into the assumptions! These are:

  • The observations are drawn from a normal distribution
  • The standard deviations are the same between the two groups
  • The observations are independent

So, before we attempt to interpret these results, we need to make some plots. We will be using a very nice accessory package to dplyr: ggplot2. The package ggplot2 works again via a grammar, which is loosly like ‘what am I plotting?’ + ‘what does the plot look like’? I suggest you look at the suggested link to get familiar with ggplot2.

ggplot(data = flightDataTB_ttest) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = ORIGIN, y = DEP_DELAY_NEW))
## Warning: Removed 1157 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

This is somewhat helpful. We can tell right away that the observations are positively skewed and hence not from a normal distribution. Additionally, we can see that there was one flight that was particularly delayed from DFW. Let’s make a visualization based on a density estimator such as a histogram (see Figure 1.3 in APM for an example)

ggplot(data = flightDataTB_ttest, mapping = aes(x = DEP_DELAY_NEW, fill = ORIGIN)) + 
  geom_histogram(alpha=0.2, position="identity")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 1157 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

This is a count-based histogram. It is usually better to look at the density (this just divides each count by the number of observation). Also, let’s pick a bigger binwidth

ggplot(data = flightDataTB_ttest, mapping = aes(x = DEP_DELAY_NEW, y = ..density.., fill = ORIGIN)) + 
  geom_histogram(alpha=0.2, position="identity",binwidth = 200)
## Warning: Removed 1157 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

Later in the class, we can re-address this using the bootstrap. What about the independence assumption? Let’s look at a plot over time for the month

ggplot(data = flightDataTB_ttest, mapping = aes(x = factor(DAY_OF_MONTH), y = DEP_DELAY_NEW)) + 
  geom_boxplot()
## Warning: Removed 1157 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

Not much to see here, maybe we can plot the median flight delay by day of month

flightDataTB %>%
  filter(ORIGIN == 'IAH' | ORIGIN == 'DFW') %>%
  group_by(DAY_OF_MONTH) %>%
  summarise(medDelay = median(DEP_DELAY_NEW, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(.) +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(x = DAY_OF_MONTH, y = medDelay))

It’s notable that two of the highest median delays occured on the first two days. Perhaps it is related to weather or maybe the holiday?
